# Python Async & Concurrency

Use the right concurrency model for the problem. Mixing models incorrectly causes subtle deadlocks and performance cliffs.

## When to use what

| Workload | Model |
|---|---|
| I/O-bound (network, disk, DB) | `asyncio` |
| CPU-bound (computation) | `multiprocessing` / `ProcessPoolExecutor` |
| Mixed / legacy blocking libs | `ThreadPoolExecutor` inside asyncio via `loop.run_in_executor` |
| Simple parallelism | `concurrent.futures` |

## asyncio rules

- Mark I/O-bound coroutines with `async def`; call them with `await`
- Never call blocking I/O inside a coroutine without wrapping it in `run_in_executor` — it stalls the entire event loop
- Use `asyncio.gather()` for concurrent independent tasks; use `asyncio.TaskGroup` (Python 3.11+) for structured concurrency with automatic cancellation
- Always cancel tasks on shutdown — leaked tasks mask errors and hold resources
- Use `asyncio.timeout()` (3.11+) or `asyncio.wait_for()` for every external call

## Common pitfalls

- Do not use `time.sleep()` in async code — use `asyncio.sleep()`
- Do not share mutable state between coroutines without `asyncio.Lock`
- Do not create a new event loop per request — reuse one loop per process
- Avoid `asyncio.get_event_loop()` in new code; use `asyncio.get_running_loop()` inside coroutines

## Libraries

- Use **httpx** (async) instead of `requests` for async HTTP clients
- Use **asyncpg** or **SQLAlchemy async** for async database access
- Use **aiofiles** for async file I/O

## Testing async code

- Use `pytest-asyncio` with `@pytest.mark.asyncio`
- Set `asyncio_mode = "auto"` in `pytest.ini` to avoid decorating every test
